    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_70878487" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/70878487" />
    <a title="Steve" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/236411-steve"><img alt="Steve" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1291695844p2/236411.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/70878487?book_show_action=true">Sep 11, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve" href="/user/show/236411-steve">Steve</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer70878487" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16079907448186238934">An artist about to paint a self-portrait was situating his mirror when it slipped through his fingers and crashed to the floor. He looked down at the shards reflecting segments of his face and liked what he saw. He also liked what he didn’t see. His mind’s eye had to fill in the gaps in his image – serendipitous disjointedness a la Picasso. <br/> <br/>Maybe this book is a little like that. The vast middle section is a profile of “infrarealist” poet Arturo Belano (Bolano’s alter ego) and sidekick Ulises Li</span>
  <span id="freeText16079907448186238934" style="display:none">An artist about to paint a self-portrait was situating his mirror when it slipped through his fingers and crashed to the floor. He looked down at the shards reflecting segments of his face and liked what he saw. He also liked what he didn’t see. His mind’s eye had to fill in the gaps in his image – serendipitous disjointedness a la Picasso. <br /> <br />Maybe this book is a little like that. The vast middle section is a profile of “infrarealist” poet Arturo Belano (Bolano’s alter ego) and sidekick Ulises Lima as told by dozens of narrators spanning 20 some years. Each mini-story was a piece of the broken glass. Some were more distant, some closer up, many were fogged or distorted. Ironically, it was often the story-tellers who were slightly insane that made the most sense. Drug-induced, sleep-deprived, and drunken insights also featured prominently (you might say expressionistically, sticking with the art metaphor). There were plenty of pieces missing, too, like with the broken mirror. For instance, what was their poetic movement all about? And what fueled their romance for the road? Some reviewer somewhere said this is a book that fetishizes the obscure. That’s a great way to sum it up.<br /><br />While reading this, I was often reminded of <i>On the Road</i>, (though at 600+ pages it must have taken Bolano longer to put together than Kerouac’s famously rushed effort). It also struck me that how much you enjoy travels with free spirits depends on how much you like them as people. I was prepared to like Belano, Lima, and their poet friends plenty, but in the end never felt like I knew them well enough. <br /><br />Another irony that I couldn’t help but think about was how a book that focused so much on poetry didn’t feature any examples. In fact, the prose wasn’t very art-worthy either, though that may not be a fair comment to make about a translated work. It’s also possible that I missed one of the points: that part of being in this avant-garde offshoot they called visceral realism (=infrarealism ) is to fly in the face of art properly conceived. Long, countercultural hair and a view that most other versifiers produce nothing but guano was closer to the mark for these guys, I think.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16079907448186238934" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


